which holds to order formula_24.

However, the contribution to the potential energy from this region for the state with a node is
formula_25
lower, but still of the same lower order formula_26 as for the deformed state , and subdominant to the lowering of the average kinetic energy.
Therefore, the potential energy is unchanged up to order formula_27, if we deform the state formula_28 with a node into a state without a node, and the change can be ignored.

We can therefore remove all nodes and reduce the energy by formula_18, which implies that cannot be the ground state. Thus the ground-state wave function cannot have a node. This completes the proof. (The average energy may then be further lowered by eliminating undulations, to the variational absolute minimum.)

=== Implication ===
As the ground state has no nodes it is &quot;spatially&quot; non-degenerate, i.e. there are no two stationary quantum states with the energy eigenvalue of the ground state (let&#x27;s name it formula_30) and the same spin state and therefore would only differ in their position-space wave functions.

The reasoning goes by contradiction: For if the ground state would be degenerate then there would be two orthonormal stationary states formula_31 and formula_32 — later on represented by their complex-valued position-space wave functions formula_33 and formula_34 — and any superposition formula_35 with the complex numbers formula_36 fulfilling the condition formula_37 would also be a be such a state, i.e. would have the same energy-eigenvalue formula_30 and the same spin-state.

Now let formula_39 be some random point (where both wave functions are defined) and set:
